text: Crystal structure of AlpK: An essential monooxygenase involved in the biosynthesis of kinamycin Wenpeng Wang a, b, Jun Li c, HuanHuan Li a, b, Keqing Fan d, Yingfang Liu a, e, * a National Laboratory of Biomacromolecules, Institute of Biophysics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, 100101, China b University of Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, 100049, China c School of Medicine, Sun Yat-Sen University, Shenzhen, 510080, China d State Key Laboratory of Microbial Resources, Institute of Microbiology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, 100101, China e Guangdong Provincial Key Laboratory of Colorectal and Pelvic Floor Diseases, the Sixth Afﬁliated Hospital, School of Medicine, Sun Yat-sen University, Guangzhou, China Article history: Received 6 January 2019 Accepted 16 January 2019 Available online xxx Keywords: Crystal structure AlpK Kinamycin

Kinamycin is an atypical angucycline which is produced by several Streptomyces spp. [1]. Kinamycin is biosynthesized by a type II polyketide synthase (PKS) gene cluster known as angucycline- like polyketide (alp) [2e4]. The biosynthesis of angucyclines start at the assembly of a linear polyketide chain by Claisen condensa- tion of short chain acyl-CoA (usually acetyl-CoA or its derivative malonyl-CoA). The nascent polyketide chain is then modiﬁed by ketoreductases, cyclases and aromatases to generate biosynthetic intermediates with angucycline-type skeleton [5,6]. After that, various tailoring enzymes catalyze the subsequent modiﬁcation steps, which are the major cause of the structural diversion of angucyclines [5,7]. FAD-dependent monooxygenases are a major family of angucycline tailoring enzymes. The biosynthetic gene clusters of angucyclines usually contain at least two conserved FAD-dependent monooxygenases. One is proposed to catalyze the 2,3-dehydration reaction and the other catalyze hydroxylation and dehydration reactions at various positions [5,6]. However, the biosynthetic gene cluster of kinamycin, as well as similar gene lomaiviticin and ﬂuostatin, has up to ﬁve FAD- clusters of * Corresponding author. Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications j o u r n a l h o m e p a g e : w w w . e l s e v i e r . c o m / l o c a t e / y b b r c Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications xxx (xxxx) xxx AlpK is an essential monooxygenase involved in the biosynthesis of kinamycin. It catalyzes the C5- hyfroxylattion of the crucial benzo[b]-ﬂuorence intermediate in kinamycin synthesis. However, the structure and mechanism of AlpK is unclear. Here, we report the ﬁrst structure of AlpK in complex with FAD. Our structure sheds light on the catalytic mechanism of AlpK. Contents lists available at ScienceDirect dependent monooxygenases, while the catalytic functions are still unclear for most of these extra FAD-dependent monooxygenases [8e14]. One of them, AlpK, is involved in the ring opening reaction of the key intermediate dehydrorabelomycin (DHR). The ring opening reaction of DHR is catalyzed by AlpJ, a unique family of oxygenase, in which the six-member B ring of DHR is opened and rearranges to a contracted ﬁve-member ring of the unstable product, the benzo[b]ﬂuorene intermediate [15]. It was proposed that AlpK catalyzed the C5-hydroxylation reaction of the benzo[b]- ﬂuorene intermediate. And it was also reported that AlpK could supply necessary FADH2 for the AlpJ catalyzed reaction [15].

AlpK is a new catalytic entity in the pHBH (p-hydroxybenzoic acid hydroxylase) family enzymes [15]. The pHBH family protein contains three domains: the FAD-binding domain, the middle domain and the C-terminal domain [16e23]. The FAD-binding domain provides the binding sites both for the cofactor FAD and the co-substrate NADPH. The middle domain possesses the sub- strate binding site and regulates the catalytic states. The function of the C-terminal domain is still unclear. Particularly, the isoalloxazine ring of FAD is the critical catalytic core in FAD-dependent enzyme. Three conformations of the FAD were observed in the structures of pHBH family proteins, known as “in” [17,18,20], “open” [16] and “out” [21,23]. The “open” conformation is considered as an essential initial step during which the FAD is exposure to the solvent and ready for the binding of substrate [16e19]. After that, the substrate enter the tunnel and localizes at the active site [16,17,19]. The © 2019 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved. conformation of FAD will be changed to “in” after substrate binding. Then, it will be reduced by NADPH and changed to the “out” conformation [16,17,19,21,23]. In this process, the structure of the FAD binding domain is also changed, and was named as “open”, “in” and “out”, accordingly [16,17,19,21,23]. Although AlpK performs important function in kinamycin syn- thesis, the mechanism of it is still unclear. Here we report the crystal structure of AlpK in complex with FAD with an “open” conformation. The structure analysis shows two putative substrate binding sites for the substrate. These results provide insight into the function and catalytic mechanism of AlpK. 2.1. Clone, expression and puriﬁcation

The AlpK gene was cloned into a modiﬁed pRSF-Duet plasmid with 6 (cid:1) His at its N-terminal. Protein expression was induced with 0.2 mM isopropyl-D-thiogalactopyranoside at 16 (cid:3)C in E.coli BL21 (DE3) for 18 h. The bacteria cell was harvested and resuspended in lysis buffer (20 mM HEPES pH 7.4, 200 mM NaCl, 5% glycerol). The cell was then sonicated in ice-bathing condition followed by high- speed centigrade at 16,000 rpm. The proteins in the supernatant were puriﬁed by nickle afﬁnity chromatography. The nickle column was washed with lysis buffer containing 30 mM imidazol, and eluted with 350 mM imidazol. The eluted proteins were then directly loaded to the gel ﬁltration chromatography with buffer containing 20 mM HEPES pH 7.4, 100 mM NaCl and 5% glycerol. 2.2. Protein crystallization The puriﬁed proteins at concentration of 25 mg/ml, 50 mg/ml and 75 mg/ml were used for initial screening using the hanging- drop vapor-diffusion at 16 (cid:3)C. Crystals with diamond-shape were obtained in 0.01 M MgSO4, 0.1M cacodylate sodium trihydrate pH 6.0, 0.8 M (NH4)2SO4. 2.3. Data collection, structure determinant and model reﬁnement

Diffraction data was collected at beamline BL17U of Shanghai Synchrotron Radiation Facility. Data was indexed and scaled with HKL2000 [24]. Initial model was solved by molecular replacement with PHENIX.phaser [25] and PHENIX.autobuild [26] using BexE (PDB:4X4J) as homologous template. The initial model was further reﬁned with PHENIX.reﬁne [27] and COOT [28]. PHENIX.validation [29] was applied to assessed the quality of model. The atomic co- ordinates and structure factors (codes 6J0Z) has been deposited in the Protein Data Bank (http://wwpdb.org/). 2.4. Structural analysis for putative NADPH and substrate binding sites Structural analysis was performed with Pymol (https://pymol. org), PISA [30] and Ligplus [31] for ligand interaction. Sequence alignment was performed using Escript3 [32]. Putative substrate binding sites and substrate binding prediction were carried out with AutoDOCKVina [33]. 3.1. Overall structure of AlpK The crystal structure of AlpK in complex with FAD was deter- mined at a resolution of 2.89 Å (Table 1). AlpK was crystalized in a P6122 space group, with one molecule in the asymmetric unit. Please cite this article as: W. Similar to other pHBH family members, the structure of AlpK is the FAD binding domain (residues 1e173 and composed of 263e377), the middle domain (residues 174e262) and the C-ter- minal domain (residues 390e491) (Fig. 1A). The FAD binding domain of AlpK serves as the catalytic domain of the enzyme. Comprising 8 a-helices (a1-a4, a6-a9) and 11 b-strands (b1-b10, b16), the FAD binding domain of AlpK is separated into head region and body region which are connected by the middle domain. The FAD cofactor in the active center is clearly shown in the FAD binding domain (Fig. 1B). The middle domain comprises 1 a-helix (a5) and 5 b-strands (b11-b15), resembling a lid, and locates on the top of the FAD binding domain. The function unclear C-terminal domain comprising 2 a-helices (a10-a11) and 4 b-strands (b17-b20) in- teracts with the body region of the FAD binding domain. The structure of AlpK highly resembles the reported pHBH family members including BexE [17] and PgaE [18]. As shown in Fig. 1C, when superposing these structures, the overall root mean square deviations of AlpK-BexE and AlpK-PgaE are only 0.59 Å and 1.31 Å, respectively. The highly identical structures indicate the functions of AlpK are comparable with those of pHBH family proteins. 3.2. Dimer formation by AlpK

A dimeric structure of AlpK is observed in the crystal structure (Fig. 2A), where the two AlpK molecules are related by a 2-fold crystallographic axis. The dimer formation pattern of AlpK is similar to that of PgaE, in which three helices (a7, a8 and a9) in the head region of FAD binding domain mediate the dimer formation. Our gel ﬁltration result conﬁrmed that AlpK exist as a dimer in solution (Fig. 2B). The interface between the AlpK dimer was further analyzed. As shown in Fig. 2C, the carboxyl group of Glu359 in a8 from one monomer electrostatically interacts with the gua- nidinium groups of Arg332 in a7 and Arg369 in a9 from another monomer. Since Arg332, Glu359 and Arg369 are conserved in pHBH family proteins, including AlpK, BexE [17], PgaE [18] and CabE [18] (Fig. 2D), our result suggests an oligomerization pattern for these pHBH family proteins. 3.3. The FAD binding sites of AlpK

In our structure, FAD interacts with AlpK by hydrogen bonds with an interface area of approx. 700 Å2. As shown in Fig. 3A, the O4 of the FAD isoalloxazine ring interacts with the NH2 of Arg214 belonging to the middle domain. O20 and O4’ of FAD interacts with the OE1 and NE2 of Gln99 respectively. Typically, O2P of FAD in- teracts with the OG1 of Thr16 which locating in an FAD binding sequence G12A13G14P15T16G17, belonging to the GXGXXG consensus motif in the pHBH family members [16e18,20e23]. In addition, the adenine ring of FAD also interacts with Lys36, Val123 and Ser161. Since the AlpK-FAD complex is crystallized without substrate or NADPH, the structure of AlpK was supposed to adopt an “open” conformation. To study the conformation of AlpK-FAD complex, we compared our structures with the structures of other pHBH ho- mologous ﬂavoproteins. Firstly, the structure of the FAD molecule in these structures was analyzed. As shown in Fig. 3B, the confor- mation of FAD in AlpK is different from the “out” conformation and “in” conformation of FADs in pHBH [19] and PgaE [18], respectively. However, it is similar with the reported “open” conformation of FAD in the mutant (R220Q) pHBH [16]. Secondly, our structure shows that AlpK protein adopt a more open conformation compared with PgaE which was reported as “open” conformation [18]. As shown in Fig. 3C, the middle domain of AlpK is distant from the FAD-binding domain. Particularly, compared with PgaE, the loop1 (residues 185e196) in the middle domain of AlpK is away the from the FAD binding domain (Fig. 3D). Table 1 Data collection and reﬁnement statistics.

Putative substrate binding sites To study the mechanism of AlpK, we docked the putative sub- strate, benzo[b]-ﬂuorene intermediate, into the AlpK-FAD structure using AutoDock Vina [33]. In our AlpK-FAD structure, an open tunnel was observed between the FAD binding domain and middle domain (Fig. 4A). The open tunnel was reported as a substrate and oxygen entrance pathway in MHBH [34] and BexE [17]. Our docking result showed two putative binding pockets for the benzo[b]-ﬂu- orene intermediate, locating at the opposite sides of the tunnel. as pocket-8.7 and pocket-7.7, respectively (Fig. 4Band C). The sub- strate in pocket-7.7 is surrounded by hydrophobic residues locating in one open entrance of the tunnel (Fig. 4D). It is close to the re- ported substrate binding and active sites in pHBH [16,23], BexE [17] and PgaE [18]. The pocket-8.7 consists hydrophobic and polar res- idues, locating near the isoalloxazine ring of FAD (Fig. 4E). It was also reported as an initial substrate binding pocket in pHBH family proteins including PgaE [18] and pHBH [16]. Residues Asp279 and Pro228, which are conserved in pHBH [16] and PgaE [18], are important to interact with the substrate. Since both pockets were reported as substrate entry pocket [16e18,20e23,34], it is difﬁcult to determine which pocket in AlpK is used for substrate enter and which pocket is used for product release. In the structure of AlpK, the space of both pockets to the active site is not enough for sub- strate entry into the active site, unless a conformational change happens after the initial substrate binding. During substrate transport, loop3 (residues 225e230) in AlpK may regulate the solvent exposure state of pocket-8.7 similar to those suggested in pHBH [16,23] and PgaE [18,35].

In this paper, we present the crystal structure of AlpK with FAD in an “open” conformation. Our structure showed that the loop1 (residues 185e196) show a signiﬁcant conformation change compared with PgaE. The loop2 (residues 286e289) may assist to stabilize the FAD “open” conformation through hydrophobic interaction by Pro286. In the “open” conformational AlpK, a tunnel exists between the FAD binding domain and middle domain. This tunnel lead to the exposure to solvent and enable the substrate entry and prodcut release. According to previous reports, the middle domain in pHBH family proteins are involved in the enzy- matic activity regulation [16e22]. Based on the AlpK structure, we hypothesis that the lid-resembling middle domain of AlpK regu- lates the enzymatic activity by affecting the exposure of FAD and substrate to the solvent. In the “open” conformation, the middle domain shifts away from the FAD-binding domain to ensure the substrate, solvent and oxygen molecule entry or release. It is assumed that the loop2 (residues 286e289) and the loop3 (resi- dues 225e230) have the potential to regulate the tunnel for the substrate transportation into the active site after substrate initial binding at pocket-8.7 or pocket-7.7. Similar to other pHBH family proteins, after the substrate binding at the active site, FAD turns into “in” conformation. Taken together, the structure proposed a substrate binding and catalyze mechanism. Further investigation is still needed to illustrate the precise mechanism of AlpK.
